[
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Computational and Applied Mathematics ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            258,
            106,
            679,
            127
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solve every problem. ",
        "bbox": [
            390,
            135,
            542,
            151
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 1. Let $f \\in C^{k+1}[-1,1]$ and $[-1,1]$ be partitioned into subintervals $I_j = [(j-1)h,jh]$ of width $h$ . Assume $p$ is a polynomial of degree $k$ which approximates $f$ in $I_j$ with ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            172,
            825,
            209
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\max  _ {x \\in I _ {j}} \\left| p _ {j} (x) - f (x) \\right| \\leq C _ {0} h ^ {k + 1},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            359,
            226,
            576,
            253
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $C_0$ is a constant independent of $j$ . Show that there exists an another constant $C$ , independent of $j$ , such that ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            273,
            823,
            306
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\max  _ {x \\in I _ {j \\pm 1}} \\left| p _ {j} (x) - f (x) \\right| \\leq C h ^ {k + 1}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            359,
            306,
            576,
            333
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(as long as $I_{j\\pm 1}\\subset [-1,1]$ , of course). ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            349,
            380,
            367
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: Pick points $0 \\leq x_0 < x_1 < \\dots < x_k \\leq 1$ , and let ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            388,
            498,
            404
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nL _ {i} (x) = \\prod_ {l \\neq i} \\frac {x - x _ {l}}{x _ {i} - x _ {l}}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            401,
            410,
            532,
            444
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "be the $l$ -th Lagrange polynomial. Let ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            450,
            359,
            465
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\Lambda = \\sum_ {i = 0} ^ {k} \\max  _ {x \\in [ - 1, 2 ]} | L _ {i} (x) |.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            387,
            465,
            547,
            506
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "On $I_{j}$ we use rescaled versions with $x_{ji} = (j - 1)h + hx_{i}$ , and ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            508,
            517,
            525
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nL _ {j i} (x) = \\prod_ {l \\neq i} \\frac {x - x _ {j l}}{x _ {j i} - x _ {j l}}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            390,
            531,
            544,
            566
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Note that $\\Lambda$ is unchanged with ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            573,
            315,
            587
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\Lambda = \\sum_ {i} \\max  _ {x \\in L _ {j \\pm 1}} \\left| L _ {j i} (x) \\right|.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            388,
            585,
            545,
            617
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Let $f_{j}$ be the interpolating polynomial on $I_{j}$ ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            621,
            401,
            636
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nf _ {j} (x) = \\sum_ {i = 0} ^ {k} f \\left(x _ {j i}\\right) L _ {j i} (x),\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            385,
            645,
            550,
            684
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "and note that also ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            693,
            233,
            705
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\np _ {j} (x) = \\sum_ {i} p (x _ {j i}) L _ {j i} (x).\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            383,
            703,
            550,
            734
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Then for $x\\in I_{j\\pm 1}$ ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            738,
            233,
            753
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\left| p _ {j} (x) - f (x) \\right| \\leq \\left| p _ {j} (x) - f _ {j} (x) \\right| + \\left| f _ {j} (x) - f (x) \\right| \\\\ = \\left| \\sum_ {i = 0} ^ {k} \\left(f \\left(x _ {j i}\\right) - p _ {j} \\left(x _ {j i}\\right) L _ {j i} (x) \\right. \\right\\rvert + \\left| R _ {k} f (x) \\right| \\\\ \\leq \\max  _ {x \\in I _ {j}} | f (x) - p _ {j} (x) | \\Lambda + \\frac {\\| f ^ {(k + 1)} \\|}{(k + 1) !} \\max  _ {x \\in I _ {j \\pm 1}} \\left| \\prod_ {i = 0} ^ {k} (x - x _ {j i}) \\right| \\\\ \\leq C _ {0} \\Lambda h ^ {k + 1} + \\frac {\\| f ^ {(k + 1)} \\|}{(k + 1) !} \\max  _ {x} | (2 h) ^ {k + 1} | \\\\ = C h ^ {k + 1}, \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            243,
            760,
            694,
            921
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "header",
        "text": "S.-T. Yau College Student Mathematics Contests 2020 ",
        "bbox": [
            254,
            69,
            683,
            85
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nC = C _ {0} \\Lambda + \\frac {2 ^ {k + 1} \\| f ^ {(k + 1)} \\|}{(k + 1) !}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            380,
            65,
            558,
            99
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 2. Consider the iteration ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            112,
            127,
            372,
            142
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nx _ {n + 1} = x _ {n} - \\left(\\frac {x _ {n} - x _ {0}}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}\\right) f (x _ {n})\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            338,
            159,
            601,
            198
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "for finding the roots of a two times continuous differentiable function $f(x)$ . Assuming the method converges to a simple root $x^*$ , what is the rate of convergence? Justify your answer. ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            214,
            826,
            250
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: The iteration may be rewritten as ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            268,
            403,
            285
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nx _ {n + 1} = \\frac {[ x _ {n} f (x _ {n}) - x _ {n} f (x _ {0}) ] - [ x _ {n} f (x _ {n}) - x _ {0} f (x _ {n}) ]}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})} = \\frac {x _ {0} f (x _ {n}) - x _ {n} f (x _ {0})}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            220,
            290,
            715,
            325
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Thus ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            329,
            151,
            343
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nx _ {n + 1} - x ^ {*} = \\frac {x _ {0} f (x _ {n}) - x _ {n} f (x _ {0})}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})} - x ^ {*} = \\frac {(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) f (x _ {n}) - (x _ {n} - x ^ {*}) f (x _ {0})}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            225,
            339,
            710,
            372
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Taylor's Theorem asserts that there is $\\xi_{n}$ between $x_{n}$ and $x^{*}$ such that ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            375,
            568,
            390
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n0 = f \\left(x ^ {*}\\right) = f \\left(x _ {n}\\right) + f ^ {\\prime} \\left(\\xi_ {n}\\right) \\left(x ^ {*} - x _ {n}\\right) \\quad \\Rightarrow \\quad f \\left(x _ {n}\\right) = f ^ {\\prime} \\left(\\xi_ {n}\\right) \\left(x _ {n} - x ^ {*}\\right).\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            233,
            397,
            700,
            415
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This implies ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            422,
            200,
            436
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nx _ {n + 1} - x ^ {*} = \\frac {(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) f ^ {\\prime} (\\xi_ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}{f (x _ {n}) - f (x _ {0})} (x _ {n} - x ^ {*}).\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            313,
            434,
            624,
            467
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Evaluating the limit as $n\\to \\infty$ $\\xi_{n}\\rightarrow x^{*}$ and ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            470,
            410,
            484
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\lim _ {n \\to \\infty} \\left| \\frac {x _ {n + 1} - x ^ {*}}{x _ {n} - x ^ {*}} \\right| = \\lim _ {n \\to \\infty} \\left| \\frac {(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) f ^ {\\prime} (\\xi_ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}{f (x ^ {*}) - f (x _ {0})} \\right| = \\left| \\frac {(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) \\lim _ {n \\to \\infty} f ^ {\\prime} (\\xi_ {n}) - f (x _ {0})}{0 - f (x _ {0})} \\right|.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            179,
            491,
            756,
            526
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Applying Taylor's expression one more time, we know there is $\\eta$ between $x^{*}$ and $x_0$ such that ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            531,
            723,
            547
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nf (x _ {0}) = f (x ^ {*}) + f ^ {\\prime} (x ^ {*}) (x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) + \\frac {f ^ {\\prime \\prime} (\\eta)}{2} (x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) ^ {2},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            295,
            553,
            643,
            582
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "So ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            589,
            135,
            601
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nf ^ {\\prime} \\left(x ^ {*}\\right) \\left(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}\\right) - f \\left(x _ {0}\\right) = - \\frac {f ^ {\\prime \\prime} (\\eta)}{2} \\left(x _ {0} - x ^ {*}\\right) ^ {2}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            316,
            598,
            619,
            628
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Therefore ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            631,
            181,
            643
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\lim  _ {n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\left| \\frac {x _ {n + 1} - x ^ {*}}{x _ {n} - x ^ {*}} \\right| = \\left| \\frac {f ^ {\\prime \\prime} (\\eta)}{2 f (x _ {0})} \\right| (x _ {0} - x ^ {*}) ^ {2}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            338,
            640,
            598,
            675
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Note the right hand side is dependent only upon $x^{*}$ and $x_0$ . Since we know $x_{n}\\to x^{*}$ , this shows the rate of convergence is linear. ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            676,
            826,
            710
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 3. Suppose $\\mathbf{A}$ is an $m \\times m$ matrix with a complete set of orthonormal eigenvectors $\\mathbf{q}_1, \\ldots, \\mathbf{q}_m$ and corresponding eigenvalues $\\lambda_1, \\ldots, \\lambda_m$ . Assume that $|\\lambda_1| > |\\lambda_2| > |\\lambda_3|$ and $\\lambda_j \\geq \\lambda_{j+1}$ for $j = 3, \\ldots, m$ . Consider the power method $\\mathbf{v}^{(k)} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{v}^{(k-1)} / \\lambda_1$ , with $\\mathbf{v}^{(0)} = \\alpha_1\\mathbf{q}_1 + \\dots + \\alpha_m\\mathbf{q}_m$ where $\\alpha_1$ and $\\alpha_2$ are both nonzero. Show that the sequence $\\{\\mathbf{v}^{(k)}\\}_{k=0}^{\\infty}$ converges linearly to $\\alpha_1\\mathbf{q}_1$ with asymptotic constant $C = |\\lambda_2 / \\lambda_1|$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            723,
            826,
            809
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: Matrix A has following eigen-decomposition ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            830,
            480,
            845
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\mathbf {A} = \\left[ \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\right] \\left[ \\begin{array}{c c c c} \\lambda_ {1} & & & \\\\ & \\lambda_ {2} & & \\\\ & & \\ddots & \\\\ & & & \\lambda_ {m} \\end{array} \\right] \\left[ \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\right] ^ {- 1},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            264,
            852,
            673,
            925
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "thus ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            71,
            145,
            84
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\mathbf {A} ^ {k} = \\left[ \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\right] \\left[ \\begin{array}{c c c c} \\lambda_ {1} ^ {k} & & & \\\\ & \\lambda_ {2} ^ {k} & & \\\\ & & \\ddots & \\\\ & & & \\lambda_ {m} ^ {k} \\end{array} \\right] \\left[ \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\right] ^ {- 1}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            259,
            88,
            676,
            162
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The power method reduces to ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            167,
            312,
            181
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\mathbf {v} ^ {(k)} = \\mathbf {A} ^ {k} \\frac {\\mathbf {v} ^ {(0)}}{\\lambda_ {1} ^ {k}} \\\\ = \\left[ \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\right] \\left[ \\begin{array}{c c c c} \\lambda_ {1} ^ {k} & & & \\\\ & \\lambda_ {2} ^ {k} & & \\\\ & & \\ddots & \\\\ & & & \\lambda_ {m} ^ {k} \\end{array} \\right] \\left[ \\begin{array}{c} \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\end{array} \\right] ^ {- 1} \\left[ \\begin{array}{c} \\mathbf {q} _ {1}, \\mathbf {q} _ {2}, \\dots , \\mathbf {q} _ {m} \\end{array} \\right] \\left[ \\begin{array}{c} \\frac {\\alpha_ {1}}{\\lambda_ {1} ^ {k}} \\\\ \\frac {\\alpha_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1} ^ {k}} \\\\ \\vdots \\\\ \\frac {\\alpha_ {m}}{\\lambda_ {1} ^ {k}}, \\end{array} \\right] \\\\ = \\alpha_ {1} \\mathbf {q} _ {1} + \\sum_ {j = 2} ^ {m} \\left(\\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {1}}\\right) ^ {k} \\alpha_ {j} \\mathbf {q} _ {j}, \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            187,
            186,
            746,
            357
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "from this we deduce $\\mathbf{v}^{(k)}\\to \\alpha_{1}\\mathbf{q}_{1}$ as $k\\rightarrow \\infty$ , since $|\\lambda_j / \\lambda_1| < 1$ for $j = 2,\\ldots ,m$ ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            363,
            638,
            381
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "To show the convergence is linear with asymptotic constant $C = |\\lambda_2 / \\lambda_1|$ we need to verify the limit ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            387,
            771,
            404
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\lim  _ {k \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac {\\left|\\left| e ^ {(k + 1)} \\right|\\right|}{\\left|\\left| e ^ {(k)} \\right|\\right|} = \\lim  _ {k \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac {\\left|\\left| \\mathbf {v} ^ {(k + 1)} - \\alpha_ {1} \\mathbf {q} _ {1} \\right|\\right|}{\\left|\\left| \\mathbf {v} ^ {(k)} - \\alpha_ {1} \\mathbf {q} _ {1} \\right|\\right|} = \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| \\quad (\\text {h e r e} | | \\cdot | | d e n o t e s t h e L _ {2} - n o r m).\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            187,
            409,
            746,
            445
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Note that $e^{(k)} = \\sum_{j=2}^{m} \\left( \\frac{\\lambda_j}{\\lambda_1} \\right)^k \\alpha_j \\mathbf{q}_j$ , using the orthonormality of the eigenvectors we have ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            450,
            687,
            478
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n| | e ^ {(k)} | | ^ {2} = \\sum_ {j = 2} ^ {m} \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| ^ {2 k} | \\alpha_ {j} | ^ {2} = \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| ^ {2 k} \\left(| \\alpha_ {2} | ^ {2} + \\sum_ {j = 3} ^ {m} \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {2}} \\right| ^ {2 k} | \\alpha_ {j} | ^ {2}\\right),\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            264,
            484,
            671,
            531
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "similarly ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            536,
            176,
            551
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\left| \\left| e ^ {(k + 1)} \\right| \\right| ^ {2} = \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| ^ {2 (k + 1)} \\left(\\left| \\alpha_ {2} \\right| ^ {2} + \\sum_ {j = 3} ^ {m} \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {2}} \\right| ^ {2 (k + 1)} \\left| \\alpha_ {j} \\right| ^ {2}\\right).\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            295,
            549,
            640,
            595
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Thus ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            598,
            151,
            611
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\lim  _ {k \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac {\\left|\\left| e ^ {(k + 1)} \\right|\\right|}{\\left|\\left| e ^ {(k)} \\right|\\right|} = \\lim  _ {k \\rightarrow \\infty} \\left(\\frac {\\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| ^ {2 (k + 1)} \\left(| \\alpha_ {2} | ^ {2} + \\sum_ {j = 3} ^ {m} \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {2}} \\right| ^ {2 (k + 1)} | \\alpha_ {j} | ^ {2}\\right)}{\\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| ^ {2 k} \\left(| \\alpha_ {2} | ^ {2} + \\sum_ {j = 3} ^ {m} \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {j}}{\\lambda_ {2}} \\right| ^ {2 k} | \\alpha_ {j} | ^ {2}\\right)}\\right) ^ {\\frac {1}{2}} \\\\ = \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| \\frac {| \\alpha_ {2} |}{| \\alpha_ {2} |} \\quad (\\text {w e h a v e u s e d} | \\lambda_ {2} | > | \\lambda_ {3} | \\geq | \\lambda_ {j} | \\text {f o r} j > 3) \\\\ = \\left| \\frac {\\lambda_ {2}}{\\lambda_ {1}} \\right| \\quad (\\text {s i n c e} \\alpha_ {2} \\neq 0). \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            222,
            616,
            714,
            761
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 4. For the initial value problem $y' = f(t, y)$ , $y(0) = y_0$ on the interval $[0, T]$ , consider the implicit two-step method ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            790,
            826,
            824
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\ny _ {n + 1} = \\frac {4}{3} y _ {n} - \\frac {1}{3} y _ {n - 1} + \\frac {2 h}{3} f \\left(t _ {n + 1}, y _ {n + 1}\\right),\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            323,
            835,
            612,
            868
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\ny _ {1} = y _ {0} + h f (t _ {1}, y _ {0}),\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            325,
            872,
            473,
            888
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $h$ is the step size and $t_n = nh$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            904,
            375,
            921
        ],
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(a) What is the order of the accuracy of the scheme? ",
            "(b) Check the stability of the scheme by analyzing the stability polynomial? ",
            "(c) Find the stability region of the scheme. "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            125,
            75,
            674,
            142
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: (a) Let $y(t)$ be the exact solution, then the truncation error of form ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            165,
            619,
            179
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nh \\tau_ {n + 1} := y (t _ {n + 1}) - \\left(\\frac {4}{3} y (t _ {n}) - \\frac {1}{3} y (t _ {n - 1}) + \\frac {2 h}{3} f (t _ {n + 1}, y (t _ {n + 1}))\\right)\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            267,
            189,
            666,
            224
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "can be estimated by using Taylor expansion to every term involved: ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            234,
            553,
            250
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} y \\left(t _ {n + 1}\\right) = y _ {n} + h y _ {n} ^ {\\prime} + \\frac {1}{2} h ^ {2} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime} + \\frac {1}{6} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O \\left(h ^ {4}\\right), \\\\ - \\frac {1}{3} y _ {n - 1} = - \\frac {1}{3} y _ {n} + \\frac {1}{3} h y _ {n} ^ {\\prime} - \\frac {1}{6} h ^ {2} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime} + \\frac {1}{1 8} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O \\left(h ^ {4}\\right), \\\\ \\frac {2 h}{3} f \\left(t _ {n + 1}, y _ {n + 1}\\right) = \\frac {2 h}{3} y _ {n + 1} ^ {\\prime} = \\frac {2}{3} h y _ {n} ^ {\\prime} + \\frac {2}{3} h ^ {2} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime} + \\frac {1}{3} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O \\left(h ^ {4}\\right). \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            254,
            260,
            681,
            351
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Hence ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            361,
            158,
            373
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} h \\tau_ {n + 1} = \\left[ y _ {n} + h y _ {n} ^ {\\prime} + \\frac {1}{2} h ^ {2} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime} + \\frac {1}{6} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O (h ^ {4}) \\right] - \\left[ y _ {n} + h y _ {n} ^ {\\prime} + \\frac {1}{2} h ^ {2} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime} + \\frac {7}{1 8} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O (h ^ {4}) \\right] \\\\ = - \\frac {2}{9} h ^ {3} y _ {n} ^ {\\prime \\prime \\prime} + O \\left(h ^ {4}\\right). \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            163,
            382,
            772,
            448
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The method has order of accuracy 2. ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            458,
            354,
            473
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(b) Apply the method to the case $f = 0$ , then ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            488,
            410,
            503
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\ny _ {n + 1} - \\frac {4}{3} y _ {n} + \\frac {1}{3} y _ {n - 1} = 0,\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            383,
            513,
            553,
            542
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "when for ansatz of form $y_{n} = \\gamma^{n}$ gives the stability polynomial ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            553,
            526,
            569
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\gamma^ {2} - \\frac {4}{3} \\gamma + \\frac {1}{3} = 0,\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            408,
            579,
            529,
            609
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "which has nonzero roots $\\gamma = 1, \\frac{1}{3}$ . Since $|\\gamma| \\leq 1$ and $\\gamma = 1$ as a single root, the method is stable. ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            619,
            740,
            637
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(c) Consider the stiff problem $y' = \\lambda y$ . The method becomes ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            650,
            513,
            665
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\ny _ {n + 1} = \\frac {4}{3} y _ {n} - \\frac {1}{3} y _ {n - 1} + \\frac {2}{3} h \\lambda y _ {n + 1},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            357,
            675,
            578,
            705
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "which has stability polynomial ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            715,
            316,
            731
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n(3 - 2 h \\lambda) \\gamma^ {2} - 4 \\gamma + 1 = 0.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            380,
            729,
            555,
            746
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "So the stability region is given by ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            753,
            334,
            768
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\left| \\frac {4 \\pm \\sqrt {1 6 - 4 (3 - 2 h \\lambda)}}{2 (3 - 2 h \\lambda)} \\right| <   1,\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            374,
            766,
            563,
            806
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            814,
            140,
            825
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nR = \\left\\{h \\lambda \\in C: \\left| \\frac {2 \\pm \\sqrt {1 - 2 h \\lambda}}{3 - 2 h \\lambda} \\right| <   1 \\right\\}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            336,
            824,
            596,
            866
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 5. Suppose the difference scheme $u^{n + 1} = Bu^n$ is stable, and $C(\\Delta t)$ is a bounded family of operators. Show that the scheme ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            75,
            826,
            112
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nu ^ {n + 1} = (B + \\Delta t C (\\Delta t)) u ^ {n}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            377,
            130,
            558,
            148
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "is stable. ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            170,
            181,
            185
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: Suppose $\\| B^k \\| \\leq K_1$ for $0 \\leq k \\leq n$ and $\\| C(\\Delta t) \\| \\leq K_2$ . It suffices to show $(B + \\Delta t C(\\Delta t))^n$ is bounded for $n\\Delta t \\leq T$ . This will consist of $2^n$ terms, of which $\\binom{n}{j}$ terms involve $j$ factors $\\Delta t C$ interspersed in $n - j$ factors $B$ ; the latter can occur in at most $j + 1$ sequences of consecutive factors, the norm of each sequence being bounded by $K_1$ , and hence the norm of each such term by $K_2^j K_1^{j+1}$ . Thus overall we obtain the bound ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            205,
            826,
            297
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\| \\bigl(B + \\Delta tC(\\Delta t)\\bigr)^{n}\\| \\leq \\sum_{j = 0}^{n}\\left( \\begin{array}{c}n\\\\ j \\end{array} \\right)K_{1}^{j + 1}(\\Delta tK_{2})^{j} \\\\ = K _ {1} \\left(1 + \\Delta t K _ {1} K _ {2}\\right) ^ {n} \\\\ \\leq K _ {1} e ^ {n \\Delta t K _ {1} K _ {2}} \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            318,
            304,
            617,
            383
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "which is bounded for $n\\Delta t \\leq T$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            397,
            316,
            412
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Problem 6. Let $A$ be an $m \\times m$ nonsingular matrix. Suppose $\\inf_{p_n \\in P^n} ||p_n(A)|| = ||p^*(A)|| > 0$ where $P^n$ denotes the set of all degree- $n$ monic polynomials: ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            426,
            826,
            460
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nP ^ {n} = \\left\\{p: p \\text {i s a p o l y n o m i a l o f d e g r e e} n, p (z) = z ^ {n} + \\dots \\right\\}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            254,
            479,
            679,
            500
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Prove that $p^*$ is unique. ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            518,
            284,
            536
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Solution: We prove by contradiction. Assuming there are two $p_i$ for $i = 1,2$ as minimizers, then $p = (p_1 + p_2) / 2$ shares the same 2-norm, ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            556,
            823,
            585
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\left\\| p _ {1} \\right\\| = \\left\\| p _ {2} \\right\\| = \\left\\| p \\right\\| = \\sigma_ {1},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            380,
            587,
            555,
            604
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where $\\sigma_{1}$ is the largest singular value. Let the SVD of $p$ be ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            609,
            503,
            625
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\np (A) = U \\operatorname {d i a g} \\left(\\sigma_ {1}, \\dots , \\sigma_ {n}\\right) V ^ {*}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            369,
            635,
            566,
            651
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Suppose $\\sigma_{1}$ is $J$ -fold, with left and right singular vectors $u_{1},\\ldots ,u_{J}$ and $\\nu_{1},\\ldots ,\\nu_{J}$ , respectively. ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            662,
            741,
            678
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "By convexity of the 2-norm, we have ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            686,
            359,
            700
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\sigma_ {1} = \\| p (A) v _ {j} \\| \\leq \\frac {1}{2} \\left(\\| p _ {1} (A) v _ {j} \\| + \\| p _ {2} (A) v _ {j} \\|\\right) \\leq \\sigma_ {1},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            295,
            709,
            640,
            739
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "which implies that ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            747,
            238,
            762
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\left\\| p _ {1} (A) v _ {j} \\right\\| = \\left\\| p _ {2} (A) v _ {j} \\right\\| = \\sigma_ {1}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            370,
            761,
            565,
            779
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "and ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            784,
            140,
            796
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n(p _ {1} - p _ {2}) v _ {j} = 0, 1 \\leq j \\leq J.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            377,
            797,
            558,
            815
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Similarly we can show that $(p_1^* - p_2^*)u_j = 0$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            820,
            403,
            837
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Construct $q \\in P^n$ using $p_1 - p_2$ so that $q\\nu_j = 0$ and $q^* u_j = 0$ . For a fixed $\\epsilon \\in (0,1)$ , define ",
        "bbox": [
            111,
            844,
            705,
            859
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\np _ {\\epsilon} = (1 - \\epsilon) p + \\epsilon q \\in P ^ {n}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            380,
            869,
            553,
            887
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Hence ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            896,
            160,
            910
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\np _ {\\epsilon} ^ {*} p _ {\\epsilon} v _ {j} = (1 - \\epsilon) p _ {\\epsilon} ^ {*} p (A) v _ {j} = (1 - \\epsilon) \\sigma_ {1} p _ {\\epsilon} ^ {*} u _ {j} = (1 - \\epsilon) ^ {2} \\sigma_ {1} ^ {2} v _ {j}.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            269,
            910,
            666,
            929
        ],
        "page_idx": 4
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This says that $p_{\\epsilon}$ has right singular vector $\\nu_{1},\\ldots ,\\nu_{J}$ corresponding to the singular value $(1 - \\epsilon)\\sigma_{1}$ . ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            71,
            758,
            87
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "There are two cases to consider: ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            95,
            326,
            108
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(1) $\\| p_{\\epsilon}\\| = (1 - \\epsilon)\\sigma_{1} < \\sigma_{1}$ is not the largest singular value, we see a contradiction. ",
            "(2) None of $\\nu_{1},\\ldots ,\\nu_{J}$ correspond to the largest singular value of $p_\\epsilon$ . Using this fact and "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            127,
            125,
            710,
            162
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\np (A) = U \\Sigma V ^ {*},\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            418,
            179,
            517,
            196
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "we have ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            203,
            173,
            215
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\begin{array}{l} \\| p _ {\\epsilon} (A) \\| = \\| p _ {\\epsilon} (A) V \\| = \\| p _ {\\epsilon} (A) \\left[ v _ {J + 1}, \\dots , v _ {n} \\right] \\| \\\\ = \\| (1 - \\epsilon) p (A) [ v _ {J + 1}, \\dots v _ {n} ] + \\epsilon q (A) [ v _ {J + 1}, \\dots , v _ {n} ] \\| \\\\ \\leq (1 - \\epsilon) \\| [ u _ {J + 1}, \\dots u _ {n} ] \\mathrm {d i a g} (\\sigma_ {J + 1}, \\dots , \\sigma_ {n}) \\| + \\epsilon \\| q (A) [ v _ {J + 1}, \\dots , v _ {n} ] \\| \\\\ \\leq (1 - \\epsilon) \\sigma_ {J + 1} + \\epsilon \\| q (A) [ v _ {J + 1}, \\dots , v _ {n} ] \\| \\rightarrow \\sigma_ {J + 1} <   \\sigma_ {J} = \\sigma_ {1} \\\\ \\end{array}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            215,
            229,
            718,
            301
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "for $\\epsilon$ small. This again leads to a contradiction. The uniqueness proof is complete. ",
        "bbox": [
            112,
            316,
            653,
            330
        ],
        "page_idx": 5
    }
]